'''Wallis and Futuna''', officially the '''Territory of Wallis and Futuna Islands''' ([[French language|French]]: ''Wallis-et-Futuna'' or ''Territoire des îles Wallis-et-Futuna'', [[Fakauvea]] and [[Futunan language|Fakafutuna]]: ''Uvea mo Futuna''), is a [[Polynesia]]n French island territory (but not part of, or even contiguous with, [[French Polynesia]]) in the [[Oceania|South Pacific]] between [[Fiji]] and [[Samoa]]. It is made up of three main [[volcano|volcanic]] [[tropical]] [[island]]s and a number of tiny islets. The territory is split into two island groups lying about 260 km apart:

*[[Wallis Island]]s (Uvea), in the north
**[[Wallis Island]] (Uvea)
*[[Hoorn Islands]] (Futuna Islands), in the south
**[[Futuna Island, Wallis and Futuna|Futuna]]
**[[Alofi Island|Alofi]]

Since 2003 Wallis and Futuna has been a [[French_overseas_departments_and_territories#Overseas_Collectivities|French overseas collectivity]] (''[[collectivité d'outre-mer]]'', or ''COM''). Between 1961 and 2003, it had the status of a French overseas territory (''[[territoire d'outre-mer]]'', or ''TOM'').
